The proposed function puts the application action, delivery mechanism, and persistence detail in one place. That is the main production issue. `NextRequest`/`NextResponse`, Prisma queries, and Prisma model types are all crossing into the same unit that also owns the approval rule and invoice creation flow.

The smallest production design is:

```ts
// invoice/application/create-invoice.ts
export type CreateInvoiceRequest = {
  orderId: string;
};

export type CreateInvoiceResponse = {
  invoiceId: string;
  totalCents: number;
};

export type OrderForInvoicing = {
  id: string;
  status: "APPROVED" | "PENDING" | "CANCELLED";
  lines: ReadonlyArray<{ amountCents: number }>;
};

export interface LoadOrderForInvoicing {
  byId(orderId: string): Promise<OrderForInvoicing | null>;
}

export interface SaveInvoice {
  save(invoice: { orderId: string; totalCents: number }): Promise<{ id: string }>;
}

export class OrderNotApprovedError extends Error {}
export class OrderNotFoundError extends Error {}

export class CreateInvoice {
  constructor(
    private readonly loadOrder: LoadOrderForInvoicing,
    private readonly saveInvoice: SaveInvoice,
  ) {}

  async execute(request: CreateInvoiceRequest): Promise<CreateInvoiceResponse> {
    const order = await this.loadOrder.byId(request.orderId);
    if (!order) throw new OrderNotFoundError();
    if (order.status !== "APPROVED") throw new OrderNotApprovedError();

    const totalCents = order.lines.reduce((sum, line) => sum + line.amountCents, 0);
    const saved = await this.saveInvoice.save({ orderId: order.id, totalCents });

    return { invoiceId: saved.id, totalCents };
  }
}
```

Ownership should be:

- Application layer owns `CreateInvoiceRequest`, `CreateInvoiceResponse`, `LoadOrderForInvoicing`, and `SaveInvoice`.
- The approval check and total calculation live in the use case.
- Prisma owns its own row/query shapes only inside adapter implementations.
- Next.js owns HTTP request parsing and HTTP response formatting only inside the route handler.

Translation should happen only at the edges:

```ts
// invoice/adapters/http/next-create-invoice-route.ts
import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from "next/server";
import { createInvoiceHandler } from "@/infrastructure/invoice/wiring";
import { OrderNotApprovedError, OrderNotFoundError } from "@/invoice/application/create-invoice";

export async function POST(request: NextRequest): Promise<NextResponse> {
  const orderId = request.nextUrl.searchParams.get("orderId");
  if (!orderId) {
    return NextResponse.json({ error: "orderId required" }, { status: 400 });
  }

  try {
    const result = await createInvoiceHandler.execute({ orderId });
    return NextResponse.json({ id: result.invoiceId, totalCents: result.totalCents }, { status: 201 });
  } catch (error) {
    if (error instanceof OrderNotFoundError) {
      return NextResponse.json({ error: "order not found" }, { status: 404 });
    }
    if (error instanceof OrderNotApprovedError) {
      return NextResponse.json({ error: "not approved" }, { status: 409 });
    }
    throw error;
  }
}
```

```ts
// invoice/adapters/persistence/prisma-order-reader.ts
import { prisma } from "@/infrastructure/prisma";
import type { LoadOrderForInvoicing, OrderForInvoicing } from "@/invoice/application/create-invoice";

export class PrismaOrderReader implements LoadOrderForInvoicing {
  async byId(orderId: string): Promise<OrderForInvoicing | null> {
    const row = await prisma.order.findUnique({
      where: { id: orderId },
      include: { lines: true },
    });
    if (!row) return null;

    return {
      id: row.id,
      status: row.status,
      lines: row.lines.map((line) => ({ amountCents: line.amountCents })),
    };
  }
}
```

```ts
// invoice/adapters/persistence/prisma-invoice-writer.ts
import { prisma } from "@/infrastructure/prisma";
import type { SaveInvoice } from "@/invoice/application/create-invoice";

export class PrismaInvoiceWriter implements SaveInvoice {
  async save(invoice: { orderId: string; totalCents: number }): Promise<{ id: string }> {
    const row = await prisma.invoice.create({ data: invoice });
    return { id: row.id };
  }
}
```

```ts
// infrastructure/invoice/wiring.ts
import { CreateInvoice } from "@/invoice/application/create-invoice";
import { PrismaOrderReader } from "@/invoice/adapters/persistence/prisma-order-reader";
import { PrismaInvoiceWriter } from "@/invoice/adapters/persistence/prisma-invoice-writer";

export const createInvoiceHandler = new CreateInvoice(
  new PrismaOrderReader(),
  new PrismaInvoiceWriter(),
);
```

This is the smallest design that keeps the policy independent:

- The use case has no `next/server` import.
- The use case has no Prisma import.
- Prisma model types do not leak inward.
- HTTP status codes and JSON shapes are decided in the Next adapter.
- Concrete construction happens in outer wiring, not inside the use case.

If you want the absolute minimum boundary set, you do not need a separate domain entity yet. The approval rule and total calculation are simple enough to stay in one focused application use case with plain internal models and two ports.
